# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mitre-d3fend
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mitre-d3fend/about] In project work for our sponsors, we have repeatedly encountered the need for a model that can precisely specify cybersecurity countermeasure components and capabilities.
[src:mitre-d3fend/about] Furthermore, it is necessary that practitioners know not only what threats a capability claims to address, but specifically *how* those threats are addressed from an engineering perspective, and under what circumstances the solution would work.
[src:mitre-d3fend/about] This knowledge is essential to estimate operational applicability, identify strengths and weaknesses, and develop enterprise solutions comprising multiple capabilities.
[src:mitre-d3fend/about] To address this recurring need in the near-term, we created D3FEND, a framework in which we encode a countermeasure knowledge base, but more specifically, a knowledge graph.
[src:mitre-d3fend/about] The graph contains semantically rigorous types and relations that define both the key concepts in the cybersecurity countermeasure domain and the relations necessary to link those concepts to each other.
[src:mitre-d3fend/about] We ground each of the concepts and relations to particular references in the cybersecurity literature.
[src:mitre-d3fend/about] Numerous sources of research and development literature, to include a targeted sample of over 500 countermeasure patents from the U.S.
[src:mitre-d3fend/about] Patent Office from the years 2001 to 2018, served as the source material to build this knowledge graph.
[src:mitre-d3fend/about] To demonstrate the value of this approach in practice, the graph supports queries that can inferentially map cybersecurity countermeasures to offensive tactics, techniques, and procedures.
[src:mitre-d3fend/about] Our longer-term vision is to leverage the *linked open data* available on research literature and apply machine learning, in particular semi-supervised methods, to assist in maintaining the D3FEND knowledge graph over time.
[src:mitre-d3fend/about] Finally, we welcome community feedback on D3FEND.
[src:mitre-d3fend/about] This research was funded by the Cybersecurity Directorate of the National Security Agency under contract W56KGU-18-D-0004.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] In computer security a **countermeasure** is an action, device, procedure, or technique that reduces a threat, vulnerability, or attack, eliminating or preventing it by minimizing the harm it can cause.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] It can also include discovering and reporting vunerabilities so that corrective action can be taken.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] The definition is given in IETF RFC 2828 and CNSS Instruction No.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] 4009 dated 26 April 2010 by the Committee on National Security Systems.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] The deployment of a set of security services to protect against a security threat.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] In telecommunications, communication countermeasures are defined as security services as part of the OSI Reference model by ITU-T X.800 Recommendation.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] X.800 and ISO ISO 7498-2 (Information processing systems – Open systems interconnection – Basic Reference Model – Part 2: Security architecture are technically aligned.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] A resource (both physical or logical) can have one or more vulnerabilities that can be exploited by a threat agent in a threat action.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] The result can potentially compromise the confidentiality, integrity or availability properties of these resources (potentially different than the vulnerable one) of the organization and other involved parties (customers, suppliers).
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] The so-called CIA triad is the basis of information security.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] The attack can be active when it attempts to alter system resources or affect their operation: so it compromises integrity or availability.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] A "passive attack" attempts to learn or make use of information from the system but does not affect system resources, compromising confidentiality.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] A threat is a potential for violation of security, which exists when there is a circumstance, capability, action, or event that could breach security and cause harm.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] That is, a threat is a possible danger enabling the exploitation of a vulnerability.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] A threat can be either "intentional" (i.e., intelligent; e.g., an individual cracker or a criminal organization) or "accidental" (e.g., the possibility of a computer malfunctioning, or the possibility of an "act of God" such as an earthquake, fire, or tornado).
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] If a potential malicious actor has physical access to a computer system, they have a greater chance of inflicting harm upon it.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] Devices such as a USB Killer may be used to damage or render completely unusable anything with a connection to the motherboard of a computer, such as a USB port, video port, Ethernet port, or serial port.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] Without proper protection, these devices may result in the destruction of ports, adapter cards, storage devices, RAM, motherboards, CPUs, or anything physically connected to the device attacked, such as monitors, flash drives, or wired switches.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] These types of devices can even be used to damage smartphones and cars, as well.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] This threat can be mitigated by not installing or restricting physical access to easily accessible ports in situations where they are not necessary.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] A port-closing lock which permanently disables access to a port short of the actual port being disassembled.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] When it is necessary for a port to be accessible, an optocoupler can allow for a port to send and receive data to a computer or device without a direct electrical connection, preventing the computer or device from receiving any dangerous voltage from an external device.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] In an unsecured scenario, a malicious actor may steal or destroy storage devices such as hard drives or SSDs, resulting in the destruction or theft of valuable data.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] If the data of a storage device is no longer necessary, data theft is best prevented against by physically destroying or shredding the storage device.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] If the data of a storage device is in use and must be secured, one can use encryption to encrypt the contents of a storage device, or even encrypt the whole storage device save for the master boot record.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] The device can then be unlocked with a password, biometric authentication, a physical dongle, a network interchange, a one-time password, or any combination thereof.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] If this device is a boot drive, however, it must be unencrypted in a pre-boot environment so the operating system can be accessed.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] Not to be neglected is the process of adding physical barriers to the storage devices themselves.
[src:mitre-d3fend/countermeasure-computer] Locked cases or physically hidden drives, with a limited number of personnel with knowledge and access to the keys or locations, may prove to be a good first line against physical theft.
[src:mitre-d3fend/extended-detection-and-response] The term was coined by Nir Zuk of Palo Alto Networks in 2018.
[src:mitre-d3fend/extended-detection-and-response] According to Chapple, Stewart and Gibson, XDR is not so much another tool as the collection and integration of several concepts into a single solution, the components varying from vendor to vendor and often including NTA (network traffic analysis), NIDS and NIPS.
[src:mitre-d3fend/extended-detection-and-response] The system works by collecting and correlating data across various network points such as servers, email, cloud workloads, and endpoints.
[src:mitre-d3fend/extended-detection-and-response] The data is then analyzed and correlated, lending it visibility and context, and revealing advanced threats.
[src:mitre-d3fend/extended-detection-and-response] Thereafter, the threats are prioritized, analyzed, and sorted to prevent security collapses and data loss.
[src:mitre-d3fend/extended-detection-and-response] The XDR system helps organizations to have a higher level of cyber awareness, enabling cyber security teams to identify and eliminate security vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-d3fend/extended-detection-and-response] The XDR solution monitors the malware detection and antivirus capabilities of the endpoint detection and response (EDR) system and many extra cyber log sources to create greater context for Security Operations Center (SOC) teams to perform faster threat detection, investigation and response.
[src:mitre-d3fend/extended-detection-and-response] XDR improves on the EDR capabilities to deploy high-grade security solutions by utilizing current technologies which proactively identifies and collects security threats, and employs strategies to detect future cyber security threats.
[src:mitre-d3fend/extended-detection-and-response] It is an alternative to reactive endpoint protection solutions, such as EDR and network traffic analysis (NTA).
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] In knowledge representation and reasoning, a **knowledge graph** is a knowledge base that uses a graph-structured data model or topology to represent and operate on data.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Knowledge graphs are often used to store interlinked descriptions of entities – objects, events, situations or abstract concepts – while also encoding the free-form semantics or relationships underlying these entities.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Since the development of the Semantic Web, knowledge graphs have often been associated with linked open data projects, focusing on the connections between concepts and entities.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] They are also historically associated with and used by search engines such as Google, Bing, and Yahoo; knowledge engines and question-answering services such as WolframAlpha, Apple's Siri, and Amazon Alexa; and social networks such as LinkedIn and Facebook.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Recent developments in data science and machine learning, particularly in graph neural networks, representation learning, and machine learning, have broadened the scope of knowledge graphs beyond their traditional use in search engines and recommender systems.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] They are increasingly used in scientific research, with notable applications in fields such as genomics, proteomics, and systems biology.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] The term was coined as early as 1972 by the Austrian linguist Edgar W.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Schneider, in a discussion of how to build modular instructional systems for courses.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] In the late 1980s, the University of Groningen and University of Twente jointly began a project called Knowledge Graphs, focusing on the design of semantic networks with edges restricted to a limited set of relations, to facilitate algebras on the graph.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] In subsequent decades, the distinction between semantic networks and knowledge graphs was blurred.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Some early knowledge graphs were topic-specific.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] In 1985, Wordnet was founded, capturing semantic relationships between words and meanings – an application of this idea to language itself.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] In 2005, Marc Wirk founded Geonames to capture relationships between different geographic names and locales and associated entities.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] In 1998, Andrew Edmonds of Science in Finance Ltd in the UK created a system called ThinkBase that offered fuzzy-logic based reasoning in a graphical context.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] In 2007, both DBpedia and Freebase were founded as graph-based knowledge repositories for general-purpose knowledge.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] DBpedia focused exclusively on data extracted from Wikipedia, while Freebase also included a range of public datasets.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Neither described themselves as a 'knowledge graph' but developed and described related concepts.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] In 2012, Google introduced their Knowledge Graph, building on DBpedia and Freebase among other sources.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] They later incorporated RDFa, Microdata, JSON-LD content extracted from indexed web pages, including the *CIA World Factbook*, Wikidata, and Wikipedia.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Entity and relationship types associated with this knowledge graph have been further organized using terms from the schema.org vocabulary.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] The Google Knowledge Graph became a complement to string-based search within Google, and its popularity online brought the term into more common use.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Since then, several large multinationals have advertised their use of knowledge graphs, further popularising the term.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] These include Facebook, LinkedIn, Airbnb, Microsoft, Amazon, Uber and eBay.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] In 2019, IEEE combined its annual international conferences on "Big Knowledge" and "Data Mining and Intelligent Computing" into the International Conference on Knowledge Graph.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] The development of large language models expanded interest in knowledge graphs as a way to structure information from unstructured text, with advances in language processing enabling their automatic or semi-automatic generation and expansion.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] The term knowledge graph has since broadened to include the dynamically constructed and adaptive graph structures, which support retrieval, reasoning, and summarization in generative systems.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Microsoft Research's GraphRAG (2024) exemplified this development by integrating LLM-generated graphs into retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] There is no single commonly accepted definition of a knowledge graph.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] There are, however, many knowledge graph representations for which some of these features are not relevant.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] The term is also used in the context of note-taking software applications that allow a user to build a personal knowledge graph.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] The popularization of knowledge graphs and their accompanying methods have led to the development of graph databases such as Neo4j, GraphDB and AgensGraph.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] These graph databases allow users to easily store data as entities and their interrelationships, and facilitate operations such as data reasoning, node embedding, and ontology development on knowledge bases.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] In contrast, virtual knowledge graphs do not store information in specialized databases.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] They rely on an underlying relational database or data lake to answer queries on the graph.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Such a virtual knowledge graph system must be properly configured in order to answer the queries correctly.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] This specific configuration is done through a set of mappings that define the relationship between the elements of the data source and the structure and ontology of the virtual knowledge graph.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] A knowledge graph formally represents semantics by describing entities and their relationships.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Knowledge graphs may make use of ontologies as a schema layer.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] By doing this, they allow logical inference for retrieving implicit knowledge rather than only allowing queries requesting explicit knowledge.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] In order to allow the use of knowledge graphs in various machine learning tasks, several methods for deriving latent feature representations of entities and relations have been devised.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] These knowledge graph embeddings allow them to be connected to machine learning methods that require feature vectors like word embeddings.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] This can complement other estimates of conceptual similarity.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Models for generating useful knowledge graph embeddings are commonly the domain of graph neural networks (GNNs).
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] GNNs are deep learning architectures that comprise edges and nodes, which correspond well to the entities and relationships of knowledge graphs.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] The topology and data structures afforded by GNNs provide a convenient domain for semi-supervised learning, wherein the network is trained to predict the value of a node embedding (provided a group of adjacent nodes and their edges) or edge (provided a pair of nodes).
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] These tasks serve as fundamental abstractions for more complex tasks such as knowledge graph reasoning and alignment.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] As new knowledge graphs are produced across a variety of fields and contexts, the same entity will inevitably be represented in multiple graphs.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] However, because no single standard for the construction or representation of knowledge graph exists, resolving which entities from disparate graphs correspond to the same real world subject is a non-trivial task.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] This task is known as *knowledge graph entity alignment*, and is an active area of research.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Strategies for entity alignment generally seek to identify similar substructures, semantic relationships, shared attributes, or combinations of all three between two distinct knowledge graphs.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] Entity alignment methods use these structural similarities between generally non-isomorphic graphs to predict which nodes correspond to the same entity.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] In 2023, researchers found success in using large language models (LLMs) in the task of entity alignment.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] This was in particular thanks to their effectiveness at producing syntactically meaningful embeddings.
[src:mitre-d3fend/knowledge-graph] As the amount of data stored in knowledge graphs grows, developing dependable methods for knowledge graph entity alignment becomes an increasingly crucial step in the integration and cohesion of knowledge graph data.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE formed in 1958 as a military think tank, spun out from the radar and computer research at the MIT Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Over the years, MITRE's field of study has greatly diversified.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In the 1990s, with the winding down of the Cold War, private companies complained that MITRE had an unfair advantage competing for civilian contracts; in 1996 this led to the civilian projects being spun off to a new company, Mitretek.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The name MITRE was created by James McCormack Jr., one of the original board members.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The name is not an acronym, although various claims that it is can be found online.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Originally always seen in upper case, MITRE began using normal capitalization around the time of the Mitretek spinoff, but both forms can still be widely found as of 2023.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In 2023, Simson Garfinkel for MIT Technology Review studied hundreds of archival documents and could not determine the origin of MITRE’s name.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Howard Murphy, a historian at the State University of New York at Oneonta, was quoted in Technology Review as saying that the company’s incorporators chose the name “MITRE” because it was the French spelling of the American English word “miter,” a smooth joining of two pieces.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE was founded in Bedford, Massachusetts in 1958, spun off from the MIT Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE's first employees had been developing the Semi-Automatic Ground Environment (SAGE) system and aerospace defense as part of Lincoln Labs Division 6.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] They were specifically engaged in MIT's research and engineering of the project.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In April 1959, a site was purchased in Bedford, Massachusetts, near Hanscom Air Force Base, to develop a new MITRE laboratory, which MITRE occupied in September 1959.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE established an office in McLean in 1963, and had approximately 850 technical employees by 1967.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE registered the first .org domain on July 10, 1985, which continues to be used by the company.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] During the 1980s, the German hacker Markus Hess used an unsecured Mitre Tymnet connection as an entry point for intrusions into U.S.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Department of Defense, Department of Energy, and NASA computer networks.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In 1966, MITRE was one to the first companies to be part of the Dollars for Scholars program.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] At the beginning the students would go door-to-door for donations, then in 1985 it became a Phone-a-thon.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE hosted the Phone-a-thon from 1996 until 2020, where it then in 2021 and 2022 due to COVID-19 became a Mail-a-thon.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] By the 1990s, MITRE had become a "multifaceted engineering company with a wide range of clients," according to Kathleen Day of *The Washington Post*.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE worked on neural network software, the long-distance telecommunications service FTS2000 for the General Services Administration, and a new computer system for the U.S.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] On January 29, 1996, Mitre divided into two entities: The MITRE Corporation, to focus on its FFRDCs for DoD and FAA; and a new company established in McLean, called Mitretek Systems until 2007 and now called Noblis, to assume non-FFRDC research work for other U.S.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE restructured its research and engineering operations in mid 2020, forming MITRE Labs.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Approximately half of MITRE's employees work under the unit, which seeks to "further extend the parent organization's impact across federally-funded research-and-development centers and with partners in academia and industry".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The nonprofit foundation MITRE Engenuity (or simply Engenuity) was launched in 2019 "to collaborate with the private sector on solving industrywide problems with cyber defense" in collaboration with corporate partners.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The foundation created the Center for Threat-Informed Defense that has 23 member organizations with cybersecurity teams, as of 2020, including Fujitsu and Microsoft.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In September 2020, Engenuity's Center for Threat-Informed Defense and partners launched the Adversary Emulation Library, a GitHub-hosted project providing downloadable emulation plans to network security groups at no cost.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The library's first plan was focused on the prominent cybercrime group FIN6.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE had previously released emulation plans for the Chinese and Russian hacker groups Advanced Persistent Threat (APT) 3 and APT29 in 2017 and 2020, respectively.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In March 2021, Engenuity created the MITRE ATT&CK Defender training program to educate and certify cybersecurity professionals.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The National Security Engineering Center, previously known as the C3I Federally Funded Research and Development Center until 2011, addresses national security issues for the Department of Defense.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE's Center for Advanced Aviation System Development (CAASD) supports the FAA, an agency within the Department of Transportation.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The organization's Center for Enterprise Modernization, which focuses on enterprise modernization, was established as the IRS Federally Funded Research and Development Center in 1998, before being renamed in August 2001.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Originally sponsored by the Internal Revenue Service (a bureau of the Department of the Treasury), the Department of Veterans Affairs joined as a co-sponsor in 2008, and the Social Security Administration joined as a co-sponsor in 2018.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE's Homeland Security Systems Engineering and Development Institute (HSSEDI) completes work for the Department of Homeland Security, such as maintaining the federal executive department's list of the 25 most common software bugs.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The HSSEDI was established in 2009, following passage of the Homeland Security Act of 2002, and along with the Homeland Security Studies and Analysis Institute replaced the Homeland Security Institute.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE's CMS Alliance to Modernize Healthcare was established in 2012 as the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services Federally Funded Research and Development Center, also known as the Health FFRDC.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The FFRDC is sponsored by the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services, an agency within the Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE has managed the National Cybersecurity FFRDC since 2014, following receipt of a "single indefinite-delivery, indefinite-quantity" $5 billion contract from the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) for a research center dedicated to cybersecurity.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE will support NIST's work "related to cybersecurity solutions composed of commercial components and the integration of technology to build trustworthy information systems for government agencies".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In October 2024, NIST renewed MITRE's contract to operate the National Cybersecurity FFRDC, extending the arrangement through 2029.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Currently, MITRE holds the contract to administer and provide management to JASON, an advisory group for the federal government made up of scientists.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE's Center for Data-Driven Policy, established in 2020, seeks to "provide evidence-based, objective and nonpartisan insights for government policymaking".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The Center for Technology & National Security, now part of the Center for Data-Driven Policy, was created to link MITRE "with senior government officials for research and development purposes".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Members of the advisory board include John F.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] U.S. military forces, especially the Air Force, were primary initial sponsors; according to *Air Force Magazine*, MITRE was created "as a special-purpose technical not-for-profit firm to perform the SAGE systems-engineering job".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The aerial warfare service branch had struggled to identify a for-profit corporation to develop the defense system, so MITRE was hired to serve as the system engineer.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE subsequently designed air defense systems for the U.S. and allies, improving aircraft and missile tracking as well as communication interception abilities.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The company also helped design the Cheyenne Mountain Complex facility in Colorado operating the North American Air Defense system.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE has completed software engineering work for the Distributed Common Ground System and helped the North Atlantic Treaty Organization create intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance (ISR) data standards.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The company also worked with the Multi-Sensor Aerospace-Ground Joint ISR Interoperability Coalition to ensure proper formatting for ISR sensor data.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In 2018, MITRE developed the "Deliver Uncompromised" strategy for the Department of Defense, proposing recommendations for supply chain security.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The firm also published a government-mandated report with recommendations for the Air Force's inventory in 2030.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The Department of Veterans Affairs hired MITRE to provide recommendation for implementation and program integration of the Forever GI Bill.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE has also focused on the great power competition; in 2020, the company published a paper about 5G networks and competition between China and the U.S.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In addition to military work, MITRE's early projects included air traffic control improvements for the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA).
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] During the 1980s, MITRE helped modernize the Air Force's airborne early warning and control system and improve the Milstar constellation of communications satellites.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The company also worked on a major overhaul of the FAA's traffic control system as well as sensor technology for tracking stealth aircraft.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In 1997, MITRE sponsored a research program related to Global Positioning System (GPS) adaptive nulling antennas.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE also provided global navigation satellite system signal generation equipment for testing at the United States Army's White Sands Missile Range.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The Air Force Research Laboratory's geosynchronous satellite Navigation Technology Satellite-3 will use MITRE's Global Navigation Satellite System Test Architecture to "implement user equipment capability".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE has worked on the traffic collision avoidance system of the Next Generation Air Transportation System (NextGen), a modernization project of the National Airspace System (NAS).
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE's Integrated Demonstration and Experimentation for Aeronautics (IDEA) Lab has assessed the impact of new technologies for the FAA since 1992.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In addition to air traffic management and aviation regulations, the group has worked on merging unmanned aerial vehicle operations into the NAS as well as defining how the system will function in 2035, a decade after the scheduled implementation of NextGen.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE has explored the use of mobile devices for communicating instrument flight rules, specifically clearances at airports lacking Pre-Departure Clearance/Data Comm Clearance.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The company's Pacer web application uses System Wide Information Management and Traffic Flow Management System data as well as airline and general aviation departure schedules to "improve the way that general aviation operators file for and obtain departure clearances".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE has also completed air traffic control and safety work for the Civil Aviation Authority of Singapore (CAAS).
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The company's Singapore-based unit was hired by CAAS to consider how artificial intelligence, machine learning, and speech recognition could be used to improve air traffic management systems.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Among MITRE's innovations was a "speech recognition prototype that will automate and shorten the transcription process during an aviation incident investigation".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE and the Naval Research Laboratory developed the Frequency-scaled Ultra-wide Spectrum Element (FUSE) antenna to increase the data transfer speed between ground users and satellites.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Meshbed, a CubeSat launched into orbit by the Indian Space Research Organisation's Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle in November 2019, will test the antenna's effectiveness.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE has received three patents for the antenna.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The framework has been used by the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency and the FBI.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Version 14.1 was released in October 2023.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] According to a 2020 study published by the University of California, Berkeley and security software company McAfee, 80 percent of companies use the framework for cybersecurity.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The Structured Threat Information eXchange (STIX), described as a "machine-to-machine cyber threat information-sharing language", was developed by MITRE and the Department of Homeland Security.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The program facilitates information sharing between industry, critical infrastructure operators and government in order to blunt cyberattacks" and allows participants to share data via the Trusted Automated eXchange of Indicator Information (TAXII).
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Program governance was granted to the global nonprofit consortium OASIS in 2015, and STIX 2.0 was approved in 2017.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Air Force awarded a $463 million contract to continue work for the National Security Engineering Center, an FFRDC supporting the Department of Defense and Intelligence Community.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The contract will provide cybersecurity, electronics, information technology, sensors, and systems engineering services in Bedford and McLean for one year.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Microsoft and MITRE partnered on the open source Adversarial Machine Learning Threat Matrix in collaboration with IBM, Nvidia, and academic institutions.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Launched in October 2020, the framework is "designed to organize and catalogue known techniques for attacks against machine-learning systems, to inform security analysts and provide them with strategies to detect, respond and remediate against threats".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In February 2020, MITRE launched SQUINT, a free app allowing election officials to report misinformation on social media; the app was being used by eleven U.S. states, as of October 2020.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The company also established the National Election Security Lab, offering free risk assessments for voting systems.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Other projects include the Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE) database of vulnerabilities and exposures related to information security and the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE) category system for software weaknesses and vulnerabilities.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE tests automation and deployment of new security tools to augment critical infrastructure security in its Cyber Infrastructure Protection Innovation Center.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The lab includes a model city, with a hospital, rail station, chemical plant, downtown area, and neighborhood that acts as a test bed to run attack simulations.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In early 2022, MITRE launched MITRE Engage, a framework that cyber defenders use for communicating and planning cyber adversary engagement, deception, and denial activities.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The project earned a CSO 50 award for security innovation and a Global InfoSec award from Cyber Defense Magazine as the market leader for deception-based security.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In early 2024, MITRE disclosed that its Networked Experimentation, Research, and Virtualization Environment (NERVE) had been compromised between January and April through the exploitation of chained zero-day vulnerabilities in Ivanti Connect Secure appliances.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The breach was contained to the NERVE research network and did not affect MITRE's enterprise network.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In April 2024, MITRE published details of its forensic analysis and security response.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE has researched cloud computing policy, helped the U.S. federal government identify fraudulent comments intended to "spoof" public support for non-existent positions during the rulemaking process, and increased the Pennsylvania Department of Revenue's delinquent taxpayer compliance rate.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE conducts research and development to solve complex health issues ranging from preventing chronic disease to accelerating health research, improving healthcare quality, and expanding health coverage.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] During the 1980s, MITRE worked on a digital radiological imaging project for MedStar Georgetown University Hospital and an upgrade to MEDLINE for the National Institutes of Health.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In 2003, the Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) commissioned MITRE to expand on work in cybersecurity and enterprise architectures to benefit healthcare systems.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) competitively selected MITRE to operate the CMS Alliance to Modernize Healthcare federally funded research and development center (Health FFRDC) in 2012 on behalf of sponsoring agencies across HHS.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In 2015, MITRE managed an assessment and reports for the VA Choice Act, which improves healthcare access and options for our nation’s veterans.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE launched research in 2017 that created Synthea, a Synthetic Patient Population Simulation that is used to generate realistic (but not real) patient data and associated health records in a variety of formats.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE's patient data set SyntheticMass, based on "fictional" Massachusetts residents, was formatted by Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources and made available to developers via Google Cloud in 2019.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In 2023, CMS awarded MITRE a new five-year contract to operate the Health FFRDC.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In 2019, MITRE and partners in the private sector released mCODE™, a core set of elements for capturing data in a standardized format in the electronic record of cancer patients to improve treatment, care coordination, and research efforts.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In this effort to combat chronic diseases such as cancer, MITRE collaborates with organizations such as Mayo Clinic, Microsoft, and the American Society of Clinical Oncology to improve prevention and care for the millions of Americans living with cancer.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MCode serves as both a common language and a model, helping facilitate a comprehensive approach to patient care and aiding research by enabling study of data throughout a cancer patient's experience and among different groups of patients. .
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] More than 70 organizations implemented mCode by 2024.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In March 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic, MITRE published a white paper claiming the number of confirmed and reported COVID-19 cases "significantly underrepresent the actual number of active domestic COVID-19 infections" in the United States.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE said the gap was because of "limited testing capability and the multi-day period of asymptomatic infectivity associated with the COVID-19 pathogen".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) funded a $16.5 million MITRE-led project to create an enduring open source tool called Sara Alert, for monitoring symptoms of Americans exposed to COVID-19.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE developed the free tool in collaboration with multiple national public health organizations as well as local and state health agencies.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In April 2020, Sara Alert launched in Arkansas and was being tested in Danbury, Connecticut as well as the Northern Mariana Islands, with data being maintained by the Association of Public Health Laboratories.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Sara Alert was being used in Idaho, Maine, Pennsylvania, and Virginia by the end of May, and Guam by October.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Since January 2021, MITRE has co-lead a coalition known as the Vaccination Credential Initiative (VCI), which is composed of over 300 technology and healthcare organizations developing a technical standard for verifying vaccination and other clinical information.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Clair William Halligan, an electrical engineer, served as MITRE's first president until 1966, when he became chairman of the company's executive committee.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] McLucas succeeded Halligan as president.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Robert Everett served as president from 1969 to 1986.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Subsequent holders of the president and chief executive officer (CEO) role included Charles A.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] On 3 September 2024, Mark Peters became the MITRE's tenth president and CEO.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In April 2025, Brian Abrahmson was appointed senior vice president and chief operating officer.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Jay Schnitzer serves as chief technology officer and chief medical officer.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] He is leading a national effort to combat COVID-19 on behalf of MITRE and 50 partner companies, health care providers, and researchers, as of March 2020.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE named Charles Clancy its first chief futurist in 2020 and restructured to create MITRE Labs.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Slater (chairman), Sue Gordon (vice chair), Maury W.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Clarke, Lance Collins, Michael Huerta, Chris Inglis, Yvette Meléndez, Mark Peters (CEO), Adalio T.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The Alliance for Clinical Trials in Oncology, American Society of Clinical Oncology, and MITRE partnered on the 'mCODE Initiative' to recommend data standards for cancer patients' electronic health records.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE supports the Homeland Security Experts Group, which has been described as "an independent, nonpartisan group of homeland security and counterterrorism experts that educates the public and government leaders, including the secretary of homeland security".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE became a founding member of the Space Information Sharing and Analysis Center, a cybersecurity project for the space industry, in 2019.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE and partners such as Harvard Innovation Labs and MassChallenge launched Bridging Innovation in 2020 to connect government agencies and startup companies.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE is a member of the COVID-19 Healthcare Coalition, which is co-chaired by Jay Schnitzer.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In June 2020, the coalition launched the COVID-19 Decision Support Dashboard, which uses public data to assess transmission trends and display color-coded indicators based on performance by jurisdiction.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE is also part of the Fight Is In Us coalition, a collaborative effort between advocates, companies, and government officials to promote plasma donation for patient treatment during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE's Countering Unmanned Aircraft Systems Challenge in 2016 invited applicants to "demonstrate systems that detect and stop drones weighing less than five pounds that present a safety or security risk".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The company's Unique Identification of Internet of Things (IoT) Devices Challenge tasked applicants with improving security for connected devices.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In 2020, MITRE participated in the National Institute of Standards and Technology's Too Close for Too Long Challenge to "help evaluate and potentially improve upon that baseline Bluetooth performance for helping detect when smartphone users are standing too close to one another".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In addition to the headquarter campuses in Bedford and McLean, MITRE has more than 60 other locations throughout the United States and around the world.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In New Jersey, two offices house approximately 60 employees, as of September 2020.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] Up to 70 percent of employees may continue working remotely, even after restrictions associated with the COVID-19 pandemic have been lifted.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE's data center in Bedford, originally built during the 1980s and known as the High Performance Computing Center since 2015, was retrofitted with a refrigerant-based cooling system, resulting in lower operating costs and a higher compute capacity.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In 2023, a large underground marine equipment testing tank opened on the Bedford campus.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] The company's McLean campus houses the Integrated Demonstration and Experimentation for Aeronautics (IDEA) Lab, as well as the Mobile Autonomous Systems Experimentation lab, which focuses on self-driving cars.
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] MITRE's laboratory in Singapore, called Mitre Asia Pacific Singapore (MAPS) assesses and displays "various safety and air traffic concepts in preparation for the future".
[src:mitre-d3fend/mitre-corporation] In June 2008, MITRE was presented with the Secretary of Defense Medal for Outstanding Public Service for "significant contributions in communications, command and control decision-making, intelligence, cyberspace, and warfighter field support, as well as research and development".
